            "value": "Adam Sharma\u2019s life is a study in precision, a trait inherited from his immigrant Indian father, an engineer, and nurtured by his Irish-American mother, a librarian in their quiet Columbus, Ohio suburb. Growing up, Adam was enamored with the grand narratives of journalism, the idea of uncovering capital-T Truth. He enrolled at Ohio State, his notebooks filled with story leads and idealistic ambitions. But in his junior year, a sudden heart attack took his father, collapsing the scaffolding of Adam\u2019s world. He dropped out of college to support his mother, his dream of being a reporter deferred, then abandoned.\n\nHe found his way to San Francisco a decade later, not as a journalist, but as something adjacent. The city promised anonymity and opportunity. He discovered fact-checking, a field that satisfied his innate need for accuracy without the relentless networking and self-promotion of reporting. He started at a small digital publication and, through sheer meticulousness, worked his way up to Senior Fact-Checker at a major online news platform. His satisfaction comes not from bylines, but from the quiet authority of striking a red line through a false claim.\n\nNow 42, Adam\u2019s life has a comfortable rhythm. He lives alone in a rent-controlled one-bedroom in the Inner Richmond, a neighborhood whose foggy, contemplative atmosphere suits him. His 3.1-mile commute on the N Judah is a cherished ritual, a time for history podcasts and observing the city wake up. Socially, he maintains a small, loyal circle, anchored by a weekly trivia night where his encyclopedic knowledge of obscure facts makes him a local legend. Romantically, he\u2019s cautious, a long-term relationship having ended five years ago.\n\nHis connection to San Francisco is that of a dedicated student. He isn\u2019t a native, but he knows the hidden stairways and the forgotten histories better than most. Adam\u2019s quiet dream is to finish the non-fiction book he\u2019s been researching for years: a detailed history of the city\u2019s cable car system. He is a man who, having lost his grand narrative, has found profound meaning in meticulously ensuring the truth of everyone else\u2019s."
